  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article, titled \"Cre-Dependent Expression of Multiple Transgenes in Isolated Neurons of the Adult Forebrain,\" authored by a team from renowned institutions such as the Max Planck Institute of Neurobiology and the Allen Institute, has garnered attention within the academic community, reflected in its 15 citations across various reputable venues.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study presents a significant advancement in neuroscience, exploring the Cre-dependent expression of multiple transgenes in isolated neurons. This research, published in PLoS ONE, underscores the collaborative efforts of leading institutions, including the Max Planck Society and the Allen Institute for Brain Science, which not only bolsters its scientific credibility but also enhances its accessibility to a global audience.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">With a total of 15 citations, the work has made its mark within prominent scientific discussions, being referenced in influential journals such as Nature Reviews Neuroscience and Molecular Psychiatry. This citation landscape speaks to the paper's relevance and the interest it has generated among researchers, particularly in the United States and the Netherlands, which are the top citing countries for this work.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Even though the work has not yet leveraged platforms for public engagement, the absence of metrics indicating broader societal discourse suggests an opportunity for future outreach. The authors may consider contributing to more informal academic discussions to enhance the visibility of their findings. Nonetheless, the internal academic reception is clear, as the work has been a foundation for subsequent research developments, reflected in the 16 instances of downstream reuse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In summary, this research contributes to a deeper understanding of transgene expression in the adult forebrain, backed by a robust institutional framework and a solid citation foundation. The engagement of prominent institutions adds a layer of prestige to the findings, solidifying its place in ongoing conversations within the field of neuroscience.</p>",
